Package com.topcoder.util.datavalidator

Serialized Fields

validators

java.util.List validators

The list of validators to use. This is initialized in the constructor to an empty ArrayList, the reference is immutable. this was changed in version 1.1 to support TopCoder coding conventions

Class com.topcoder.util.datavalidator.AbstractObjectValidator extends java.lang.Object implements Serializable

Serialized Fields

id

java.lang.String id

This is the id of this validator and is used to uniquely identify this validator amongst other validators in a composite validator for example. This is set through a dedicated setter and is mutable. We can also read it through a dedicated getter. Access to this must be synchronized for thread-safety. It's initialized as an empty String which means that the id has not been set.

bundleInfo

BundleInfo bundleInfo

This represents the resource bundle information used by this validator. It is set in one of the constructors to either null (not required) or to a specific named bundle. This is then used to fetch the specific message based on a resource key (which is also initialized in the same constructor) It is transient since it is not serializable. It can be changed upon serialization and subsequent de-serialization.

Serialization Methods

readObject

private void readObject(java.io.ObjectInputStream stream)
                 throws java.io.IOException,
                        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException

Specific implementation for de-serialization. Here we will allow for the resource bundle to be read back in on the other end.

Throws:
java.io.IOException - if there were any issues with reading the stream
java.lang.ClassNotFoundException - if there were any issues with JVM trying to find the specific class via class loader.

writeObject

private void writeObject(java.io.ObjectOutputStream stream)
                  throws java.io.IOException

Specific implementation for serialization. This is provided mainly as needed by the protocol since we did override the readObject. There is nothing for us to do here since reourceBundle is declared as transient and will thus not be written to the stream.

Throws:
java.io.IOException - if there are any IO issues in the stream
Serialized Fields

bundleName

java.lang.String bundleName

This is a name of a resource bundle to load up the resource message from. This is initialized in the setter but since it is not required it can be null. This is used to create a named resource bundle in one of the constructors. It can be null but cannot be an empty string.

bundleLocale

java.util.Locale bundleLocale

This is the locale used to fetch the resource data. It identifies the locale for the message key that will be used to fetch the message for the validator. It will be initialized through a setter and is mutable.

currentLocale

boolean currentLocale

This is a flag used to remember if the user set up this validator with a current locale. THis will be used by serialization to also use the current locale when being serialized. It will be initialized through a setter and is mutable. By default it is false.

messageKey

java.lang.String messageKey

This is a message key used to look up and fetch a message from a resource bundle. It will be initialized through a setter and is mutable. it is an optional variable and this it can be left uninitialized (i.e. as null)

defaultMessage

java.lang.String defaultMessage

This is a default message that can be used by any validator in case the resource bundle is not available or simply not set. This will also apply to a situation where the bundle doesn't contain the requested message. This is basically a fail safe message. It will be initialized through a setter and is mutable. It can be a null or an empty message. There are no restrictions.

Serialized Fields

eps

double eps

The epsilon value to be used in this validator. This is initialized in the constructor (optional) and must be a number that is positive or zero. This value is immutable but cannot be made final since it is statically initialized to EPSILON which acts as a default. The value cannot be NaN as well.
